The city of Cusco extends throughout the Huatanay river valley. Located on the eastern end of the Knot of Cusco, its altitude is around {{convert|3300|m|ft|abbr=on}}. North to Cusco is the range of [[Cordillera Vilcabamba]] with 4<U+2013>6000 m high mountains. The highest peak is [[Salcantay|Nevado Salcantay]] (6271 m) about {{convert|60|km|2|abbr=on}} northwest of Cusco.<ref>[http://andes.zoom-maps.com/ Andes map]</ref>

===Climate===
Cusco has a [[Oceanic climate#Subtropical Highland Climate|subtropical highland climate]] ([[K<U+00F6>ppen climate classification|K<U+00F6>ppen]] ''Cwb''). Its climate is generally dry and temperate, with two defined seasons. The dry season lasts from April through October, with abundant sunshine, and occasional nighttime freezes: July is the coolest month with an average of {{convert|9.6|C|1}}. The wet season lasts from November to March, with night frost less common: November averages {{convert|13.4|C|1}}. Although frost and hail are common, snow is virtually unheard of. The last snowfall was recorded in June 1911.

Cusco was found in 2006 to be the spot on Earth with the highest [[ultraviolet]] light level.<ref>[http://web.archive.org/web/20070614170312/http://www.niwascience.co.nz/rc/atmos/uvconference/2006/Liley_2.pdf Liley, J. Ben and McKenzie, Richard L. (April 2006) "Where on Earth has the highest UV?" ''UV Radiation and its Effects: an update'' NIWA Science, Hamilton, NZ];</ref>
