==Food==
[[File:Plaza de Armas de Cuzco.jpg|300px|thumb|The Plaza de Armas of Cusco]]
As headquarters to the Inca Empire, Cusco was an important agricultural region.  It was a natural reserve for thousands of native Peruvian species, including around 2,000 varieties of [[potato]] cultivated by the people.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.solutions-site.org/artman/publish/article_338.shtml |title=Cusco, Peru Bans GM Products To Protect Diversity Of Native Potatoes |publisher=Solutions-site.org |date= |accessdate=22 July 2009}}</ref> Recently many fusion and neo-Andean restaurants have developed in Cusco, in which the cuisine is prepared with modern techniques and incorporates a blend of traditional Andean and international ingredients.<ref>[http://web.archive.org/web/20071120020007/http://www.sazonperu.com/busqueda/ciudad/index.php?idprov=137&flag=1&iddpto=8&idio= Guide to Peruvian Food, Cusco Reference]</ref>
Also, a cacao and chocolate museum, [http://Peru.ChocoMuseo.com ChocoMuseo], recently opened in the center of the city. The purpose of this place is to teach people about Peruvian cacao and also the whole process to make artisanal chocolate. .

